The line perpendicular to $y = 2x + 5$ has slope $-\frac{1}{2}$.

So, we seek the point of intersection of the lines $y = 2x + 5$ and $y = -\frac{1}{2} x + b$, where $b$ is chosen so that $(5, 5)$ lies on the latter line. Substituting into the equation of the latter line, we get $5 = -\frac{1}{2}(5) + b$, so $b = \frac{15}{2}$.

Thus the lines intersect when $2x + 5 = -\frac{1}{2} x + \frac{15}{2}$, or $x = \frac{5}{2}$. Substituting back into $y = 2x + 5$, we find $y = 2 \cdot \frac{5}{2} + 5 = 10 + 5 = \boxed{15}$. Thus, the intersection point is $(5/2, 15)$. [asy]
